{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 18:47:01.090864", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of the network\n- Topology: 1 super-spine (AS65000) ↔ 2 spines ↔ 2 leaves; each leaf connects to one host via a /24.\n- Hosts in scope: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24 via 10.0.0.1), pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24 via 10.0.1.1).\n- Routing: EBGP across all inter-router links (/31s from 172.16.0.0/16). FRR in use on routers.\n\nHigh-level health assessment\n- Fabric control-plane is healthy: On leaf_router_0_1, all four BGP peerings are Established with expected prefixes exchanged. Other subnets across the fabric show normal reachability and RTTs.\n- One access subnet (10.0.1.0/24) is impaired: host pc_0_1 is unreachable from anywhere, including from its directly connected leaf.\n\nObserved anomalies and impact\n1) pc_0_1 is completely unreachable\n- From multiple sources (e.g., pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0) we see 100% ping loss to 10.0.1.2.\n- From pc_0_1:\n  - Cannot reach its default gateway 10.0.1.1 (100% loss).\n  - Cannot reach peer hosts (e.g., 10.0.0.2) (100% loss).\n\n2) Conflicting/incorrect routing for 10.0.1.0/24 on leaf_router_0_1\n- Linux main routing table on leaf_router_0_1 contains:\n  - blackhole 10.0.1.0/24\n  - No visible connected 10.0.1.0/24 route in the main table output, despite the interface eth4 having 10.0.1.1/24 configured.\n- FRR shows both:\n  - K * 10.0.1.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\n  - C>* 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected, eth4\n  This indicates a kernel-installed blackhole route is present concurrently with the connected route from the OS, causing ambiguity and drops in the dataplane.\n\n3) Evidence of the blackhole affecting dataplane\n- leaf_router_0_1 cannot originate traffic to the host:\n  - ping 10.0.1.2 from leaf_router_0_1 fails with “ping: connect: Invalid argument”.\n  - ip route get 10.0.1.2 returns “RTNETLINK answers: Invalid argument”.\n  These symptoms are consistent with the kernel selecting a blackhole route for 10.0.1.2/24.\n- ARP/L2 is not the issue:\n  - On leaf_router_0_1: ip neigh shows 10.0.1.2 lladdr fa:11:74:67:2d:50 STALE (MAC resolved).\n  - On pc_0_1: ip neigh shows 10.0.1.1 lladdr ae:61:2d:09:c5:57 DELAY (MAC resolved).\n  - ethtool reports link detected: yes on leaf eth4 and pc eth0.\n  This indicates L2 connectivity and ARP resolution are present.\n\n4) Control-plane status is normal\n- Leaf-router BGP summary (leaf_router_0_1):\n  - Neighbors 172.16.0.34/42/50/58 (the spines) all Established; PfxRcd ~7 each, PfxSnt ~8.\n- leaf_router_0_0 shows a normal route for its local 10.0.0.0/24 (no blackhole), further isolating the issue to leaf_router_0_1’s 10.0.1.0/24.\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Faulty device: leaf_router_0_1.\n- Faulty component: Linux kernel FIB on leaf_router_0_1 for 10.0.1.0/24.\n- Scope/impact: All traffic to/from the 10.0.1.0/24 subnet is being blackholed at leaf_router_0_1. The rest of the fabric operates normally.\n\nLikely root cause\n- An unintended blackhole route to 10.0.1.0/24 in the kernel routing table on leaf_router_0_1:\n  - Present in ip route show: “blackhole 10.0.1.0/24”.\n  - Reflected in FRR as “K * 10.0.1.0/24 unreachable (blackhole)”.\n- This blackhole route supersedes normal forwarding for destinations within 10.0.1.0/24, preventing:\n  - leaf_router_0_1 from sending replies to pc_0_1 (hence pc_0_1 cannot ping its gateway).\n  - Any remote traffic destined to 10.0.1.0/24 from being delivered (hence total isolation of pc_0_1).\n\nSupporting evidence (selected)\n- pc_0_1 routes: default via 10.0.1.1; link up; ARP to gateway resolved; yet no ping to 10.0.1.1.\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - Interface eth4: 10.0.1.1/24, link up.\n  - ip route (main): blackhole 10.0.1.0/24; ip route get 10.0.1.2 → Invalid argument.\n  - FRR: both K blackhole and C connected entries for 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - BGP: all peers up; exchanges normal.\n\nConclusion\n- The data center fabric is broadly healthy at the core and aggregation layers.\n- A local FIB anomaly on leaf_router_0_1 (kernel-installed blackhole route for 10.0.1.0/24) is the root cause of the loss of connectivity for the 10.0.1.0/24 subnet, isolating host pc_0_1.\n- No evidence of link failure or BGP control-plane failure; the issue is strictly a dataplane routing misconfiguration on leaf_router_0_1.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12565, "output_tokens": 4691, "total_tokens": 17256, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11392}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3328}}}
